            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mei Lu is a San Franciscan in her bones, a product of the city\u2019s hardworking, pre-tech boom grit. The daughter of Hong Kong immigrants who ran a small import shop in the Richmond District, her childhood was a sensory education in texture, form, and function. She spent afternoons surrounded by porcelain tea sets, carved wooden boxes, and silk tapestries, developing an innate understanding of well-made objects. This upbringing led her directly to the California College of the Arts, where she earned a degree in Industrial Design.\n\nHer career was forged in partnership. At CCA, she met Javier, a classmate who shared her frustration with the growing trend of disposable goods. In the wake of the first dot-com bust, they saw an opportunity. In 2002, they pooled their meager savings and took out a daunting loan to found \u201cForm & Function MFG,\u201d a small manufacturing firm dedicated to creating durable, sustainable, and beautifully designed housewares. The first decade was a blur of 16-hour days in their Dogpatch workshop, a period that cemented their business but contributed to the amicable end of her marriage.\n\nNow, at 54, Mei has found a hard-won equilibrium. Her son is grown and living in Portland, and her friendship with Javier remains the steadiest relationship in her life. Her daily routine is a testament to intention. She lives in a modest but comfortable row house in the Inner Sunset. Mornings begin with a walk in Golden Gate Park before she drives her Volvo across town, a 6.5-mile commute that serves as her quiet time for podcasts on metallurgy and supply chains. As Principal Designer, she still spends more time sketching and reviewing prototypes than in boardrooms.\n\nHer San Francisco is not one of cable cars and tourist vistas, but of the city's maker-spaces and industrial arteries. She feels most at home amidst the scent of sawdust and machine oil. Looking forward, Mei dreams not of expansion, but of legacy. She hopes to transition their company to be employee-owned within the next decade, ensuring its ethos endures. Her personal aspirations are simpler: to travel to Scandinavia to study furniture design and, finally, to master the art of the perfect ceramic glaze."
