            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was eight, in her parents\u2019 Richmond District shop, tracing the clean break on a celadon rice bowl her father had dropped. Instead of sadness, she felt a profound curiosity. She saw the thickness of the glaze, the pale, dense porcelain beneath. Her father explained how it was fired, how its strength was also its weakness. It wasn\u2019t a broken thing; it was a lesson in material integrity. That moment planted the seed of wanting to understand an object from the inside out, beyond its surface beauty.\n\n2.\nThe air in the bank office felt sterile in 2002, a sharp contrast to the dot-com wreckage outside. As Mei\u2019s pen hovered over the loan papers, her hand trembled. It was a terrifying sum. She looked at Javier, his own face pale but set with determination. They exchanged a brief, silent nod. In that instant, fear gave way to resolve. This wasn't just a business loan; it was a pact they made with each other against a world of things designed to be thrown away.\n\n3.\nIt was nearly midnight in the Dogpatch workshop, around 2005. The smell of metal dust hung in the air. The fax machine, a relic even then, whirred and spat out a purchase order from an esteemed design store in Hayes Valley. It was for 50 of their brushed steel utensil holders. Javier let out a whoop, but Mei just stood there, holding the flimsy paper. It felt heavier than steel. It was the first real proof that their belief in enduring objects wasn\u2019t just their own.\n\n4.\nShe remembers sitting with her husband at their Inner Sunset kitchen table, the silence punctuated by the distant hum of the N-Judah. No anger was left, only a shared, weary sadness. \u201cYour first love is the workshop,\u201d he\u2019d said, not as an accusation, but as a statement of fact. She knew he was right. The amicable end of their marriage wasn\u2019t a failure, but a quiet, painful acknowledgment of her own nature. She was built to create things, a singular focus that had left too little room.\n\n5.\nJust last year, she walked into the workshop to find a young machinist arguing passionately with a designer over the bevel of a new product. He was citing material stress and longevity. Mei didn\u2019t intervene. She just watched, feeling a wave of deep satisfaction. The ethos wasn\u2019t just hers and Javier\u2019s anymore; it had taken root in the next generation. In that young man's earnest face, she saw not an employee, but the future, and her dream of a lasting legacy began to feel possible."
